        <dc:creator><![CDATA[@RichardRuane]]></dc:creator>
        <description><![CDATA[
          <p><a href="https://forums.gauntlet-rpg.com/u/richardruane">@RichardRuane</a> wrote:</p>
          <blockquote>
              <p>Two series that I keep returning to and wish I could find gamers who really wanted to dig into them:</p>
<ul>
<li>The Vorkosigan series by Lois McMaster Bujold. Bujold writes difficult/unlikely/emotionally and socially broken protagonists that I wish were easier to create in action-oriented games without point-buy driven merits and flaws. The novels are space opera, driven by the need to solve difficult, explosive situations without resorting to violent measures, and I’d love to see that sort of thinking in more trad-style games.</li>
<li>The Riverside series by Ellen Kushner. Debauchery and duels in a fictional setting resembling regency England (or a more decadent version of the Commonwealth?). Violence is dangerous (though frequently not deadly it does end careers and start lifelong political grudges), and while magic is almost unheard of in the setting, it is strange and extremely powerful when it does rear its head.</li>
</ul>
<p>There’s also a lot of post-Lovecraftian work I’m getting a lot of inspiration from lately for cosmic fantasy (that’s not just cosmic horror): Kij Baker’s “The Dreamquest of Vellit Boe,” Victor LaValle’s “The Ballad of Black Tom,” and Waldrop and Utley’s “Black as the Pit from Pole to Pole.”</p>
          </blockquote>
          <p><a href="https://forums.gauntlet-rpg.com/t/companion-adventures/793/25">Read full topic</a></p>
